# Writing and adding Operations to a connector

Operations are the heart of a connectivity project. Once a connection is
established, the operation list enables users to integrate the described service
into their environment. Defining new operations is easy: an operation consists
of a `name` (for internal usage), a `displayName` (the one that users see) and
an `executor` (the function that runs the operation).

Operation invocations can fail. Successful invocations return a `ResultSuccess`
while failed ones return a `ResultFailure`. The meaning of failure depends on
the service in question.

> **Example**
>
> Most HTTP services signal failure using 4XX and 5XX status codes, the
> [HTTP library](#http-operations) will signal an error when it sees those
> status codes. Still, some APIs will signal errors within their response
> contents. These APIs always return 2XX status codes.
>
> If you are trying to integrate these kinds of APIs, you will need to match
> on the possible responses of your `request` and signal failure accordingly.

Operations have type `Operation<ArgsT, OkT, ErrorT <: ResultFailure, ConnT>`. Let's explain each
type parameter separately:

- `ArgsT`: The type of the arguments required for an invocation. It has to be an
  `Object` type.
- `OkT`: The resulting value of successful invocations. This means successful
  invocations will return a `ResultSuccess<OkT>`.
- `ErrorT`: This means failed invocations will return a `ResultFailure<ErrorValueType, ErrorType>`, 
  where ErrorValueType is the shape of the error value, and ErrorType describe the kind and categories.
- `ConnT`: The connection type. This is an `Object` type that describes the
  contextual information required to invoke this operation.

## Operation example

```dataweave
type DuplicateParams = {
    x: Number
}

var myOperation: Operation<DuplicateParams, Number, ResultFailure<Nothing, Error>, {}> = {
    name: "duplicate",
    displayName: "2 times X",
    executor: (args: DuplicateParams, connectionInstance) ->
      success(args.x * 2)
}
```

# The `decorator::Operation` module

Once you make an operation, there are useful tools provided to transform it into
a nicer one. The platform independent decorations are located on the
[`com::mulesoft::connectivity::decorator::Operation`] and provide useful ways to
append additional code before or after an operation invocation.


## Module Summary
- `mapInputOperation(operation, mapper)`: Applies a function before the
  operation invocation. This function adapts some other input to the type
  expected by the operation.
- `mapInputPaginatedOperation(operation, mapper)`: Applies a function before the
  paginated operation invocation. This function adapts some other input to the type
  expected by the operation.
- `mapOutputSuccessOperation(operation, mapper)`: Applies a function to the
  output of successful invocations. This function transforms the output into a
  more suitable shape.
- `mapOutputFailureOperation(operation, mapper)`: Applies a function to the
  output of failed invocations. This function transforms the errors into a more
  suitable shape.
- `mapOutputFailurePaginatedOperation(operation, mapper)`: Applies a function to the
  output of failed invocations of paginated operations. This function transforms the 
  errors into a more suitable shape.
- `paginate(operation, strategy)`: Applies a pagination strategy to the output
  of successful invocations. This pagination strategy is a function that
  receives both the original parameterization and the successful result and
  creates a `Page` from there.

# HTTP Operations

HTTP operations are one of the most common kinds of operations. For this reason
they have a dedicated module [`com::mulesoft::connectivity::transport::Http`]. This
module defines a common shape for all HTTP operations and utility functions for
encoding parameters and making requests.

The `HttpOperation<ArgsT, OkT, ErrorT, ConnT>` type shares the same shape as the
operation type. There are three big differences:
- `ArgsT` has to be a subtype of `HttpRequestType`.
- `OkT` and `ErrorT` have to be subtypes of the `HttpResponse` type (the
  results have headers, body, cookies, etc.).
- `ConnT` has to be a subtype of `HttpConnection`.

In order to honor how API spec parameters are defined, the `HttpRequestType` was created. This object 
defines the elemental parameters for all HTTP operations, which are:
- Query parameters
- URI/path parameters
- Header parameters
- Cookie parameters
- A body

An HttpRequestType object must bring a query, header, and cookie fields.
These can be empty if the HTTP Operation doesn’t require this information.
On the other hand, URI and body are optional.
This definition is a way of generalization for all the HTTP operations which they have always
the same global input structure: query, URI, header cookie and body parameters.

## HttpOperation example

Imagine the following endpoint:

http://www.mulesoft.com/user/{userId}

The HTTP operation is represented as:

```dataweave
type GetUserByIdRequest = HttpRequestType<{|
                                           uri: { userId: Number },
                                           query: {},
                                           headers: {},
                                           cookie: {}
                                         |}>

@OperationElement()
var GetUserByIdEndpoint :
        HttpOperation<GetUserByIdRequest, Any, Any, HttpConnection> =
        {
        name: "getUserByIdEndpoint",
        displayName: "Get user by id",
        executor: (parameter, connection) ->
         success(connection({method: "GET", path: "/user/" ++ parameter.uri.userId})
            as HttpResponse<Any>)
        }
```

The body and URI fields are not needed in the request structure, while query, headers and cookie have to be declared,
even if the API spec definition doesn't mention them.
Lastly, ```parameter``` is type of `GetUserByIdRequest` so to get each parameter value,
a reference to the attributes is needed, see how ```parameter.uri.userId``` is used.


The `request` function from `dw::io::http::Client` is the preferred way to
perform requests. If you need to serialize complex values into query parameters,
consider using the `addQueryParameters` function.

## Encoding in HttpOperations

Some parameters need to be encoded into a suitable string representation 
before sending them in an HTTP request. The encoding configuration should be
specified for each parameter that needs. For example, an array
query parameter, must be encoded when the final URI is built, it cannot be
sent as an array itself. Similar scenarios are handled for URI, header and
cookie parameters. The main difference between them is their 
possible encoding configuration. See https://spec.openapis.org/oas/latest.html#style-values
to check each possible encoding configuration for each parameter.

### Encoding example

See the following http operation example

```dataweave
type GetUsersByCompaniesIdEndpointRequest = HttpRequestType<{|
                                           uri: { companiesId: Array<Number> },
                                           query: { users: Array<Number> },
                                           headers: { customHeader: CustomAuth},
                                           cookie: { customCookie: CustomAuth}
                                         |}>

type CustomAuth = {username: String, pass: String}

@OperationElement()
var getUsersByCompaniesIdEndpoint :
        HttpOperation<GetUsersByCompaniesIdEndpointRequest, Any, Any, HttpConnection> =
        {
        name: "getUserByIdEndpoint",
        displayName: "Get user by id",
        executor: (parameter, connection) ->
         success(connection({
                                    method: "GET",
                                    path: "/usersByCompaniesId/" ++ serializeUriParam(parameter.uri.companiesId, config:{ style: "simple", explode: false }),
                                    queryParams: parameter.query update {
                                        case users at .users -> users <~ { style: "form", explode: true }
                                    },
                                    headers: parameter.headers update {
                                        case customHeader at .customHeader -> serializeHeaders(customHeader, config: {style: "simple", explode: false})
                                        case Cookie at .Cookie! -> serializeCookies(parameter.cookie update {
                                            case customCookie at .customCookie -> customCookie <~ { style: "form", explode: false }
                                        })
                                    }
                                    })
            as HttpResponse<GetUsersByCompanyIdEndpointResponse>)
        }
```

### Encoding URI example

According to the example, this is how an URI parameter is encoded. For each
parameter to be encoded, a call to ```serializeUriParam``` function is needed
which it needs, the parameter to be encoded and the encoding configuration

```dataweave
path: "/usersByCompaniesId/" ++ serializeUriParam(parameter.uri.companiesId, config:{ style: "simple", explode: false }),
```

### Encoding query example

Query parameters are a little bit different, the ```queryParams``` object
is part of the HTTP request object, the only thing to do here is
adding metadata to each parameter that needs to be encoded in the ```queryParams```
object. The encoding process is going to be executed internally before executing the request
```dataweave
queryParams: parameter.query update {
    case users at .users -> users <~ { style: "form", explode: true }
}
```

### Encoding header and cookie example

Similarly to query parameters, ```headers``` object is part of the http request object.
The main difference here is that a call to each serialize function is needed.
All headers except the ```Cookie``` header has to be encoded calling to the
```serializeHeaders``` function, which needs the parameter to be encoded and the
encoding configuration.
The ```Cookie``` header has a different behavior, it can include many parameters, so
a call to ```serializeCookies``` function is needed. This function requires
the cookie object, followed by the information for each parameter that needs to be encoded.


```dataweave
headers: parameter.headers update {
    case customHeader at .customHeader -> serializeHeaders(customHeader, config: {style: "simple", explode: false})
    case Cookie at .Cookie! -> serializeCookies(parameter.cookie update {
        case customCookie at .customCookie -> customCookie <~ { style: "form", explode: false }
    })
}
```

## Module Summary

- `HttpRequestBuilder`: Base type for HTTP Connection instances
- `HttpResponse<T>`: Type for HTTP responses with `T` at their bodies
- `HttpAuthenticationType`: Authentication type for HTTP connections
- `HttpConnection<ArgsT, AuthenticationType>`: Type for HTTP connection
  descriptions that require an `ArgsT` parameter in order to connect and have
  the specified `AuthenticationType`
- `BasicHttpConnection<ArgsT>`: Type for HTTP connections using the
  [basic authentication scheme] that require an `ArgsT` parameter in order to
  connect
- `defineBasicHttpConnection(validate, mapper)`: Defines a
  `BasicHttpConnection` that uses `validate` in order to check credential
  validity and `mapper` to extract the authentication schema from the
  connection parameterization
- `defineBearerHttpConnection(validate, mapper)`: Defines a
  `BearerHttpConnection` that uses `validate` in order to check credential
  validity and `mapper` to extract the authentication schema from the
  connection parameterization
- `BaseAuthSchema`: Base type for all authentication schemas
- `BasicAuthSchema`: Type describing the information needed for the
  [basic authentication scheme]
- `basicAuth(schema)`: Creates a connection instance (`HttpRequestBuilder`)
  from a `BasicAuthSchema`
- `BearerAuthSchema`: Type describing the information needed for the
  [bearer authentication scheme]
- `bearerAuth(schema)`: Create a connection instance (`HttpRequestBuilder`)
  from a `BearerAuthSchema`
- `HttpOperation<ArgsT, OkT, ErrorT, ConnT>`: Type for HTTP operations
- `parseQueryParameters(uri)`: Parses the query parameters from a given URI
- `addQueryParameters(resource, queryParams, config?)`: Serialize
  `queryParams` according to the optional config and add them to the `resource`
  specified

[`com::mulesoft::connectivity::decorator::Operation`]: ../../connectivity-language/src/main/dw/com/mulesoft/connectivity/decorator/Operation.dwl
[`com::mulesoft::connectivity::transport::Http`]: ../../connectivity-language/src/main/dw/com/mulesoft/connectivity/transport/Http.dwl
