[bearer authentication scheme]: https://datatracker.ietf.org/doc/html/rfc6750

# Paginated Operations

Given an Operation, you can decorate it using the `paginate` method, defining 
a strategy to make a Paginated Operation. The new operation should return a 
result of type `Page`

The supported strategies are:
- `Page Number Pagination`: For APIs that paginate based on a query parameter that represents the page number to get.
- `Offset Pagination`: For APIs that paginate based on an offset query parameter that requests results starting from result number N.
- `Marker Pagination`: For APIs that paginate based on a marker query parameter that points to a position in the dataset to return.
- `Hypermedia Pagination`: For APIs that paginate based on retrieving the URL of the next page in the response body or in the link header.
This strategy only supports the cases in which the next URL has the same host name and path of the current URL but changing the query parameters.

## Page Number Pagination example
If a SaaS has the following endpoint:
http://www.mulesoft.com/users?page=X

The Operation is represented as:
```dataweave
var getUsers : Operation<{page: Number}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users" ++ "?page=" ++ parameter.page})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```
To create a paginated operation, you will have to do:
```dataweave
@OperationElement()
var getUsersPaginated = pageNumberPaginated(
  getUsers,
  (page) -> page.body.items default [],
  (param) -> param.page default 0,
  (param, pageNumber) -> (param update { case page at .page! -> pageNumber })
)
```

## Offset Pagination example

If a SaaS has the following endpoint:
http://www.mulesoft.com/users?offset=X&limit=Y

The Operation is represented as:
```dataweave
var getUsers : Operation<{from: Number, limit: Number}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users" ++ "?from=" ++ parameter.from ++ "&limit=" ++ parameter.limit})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```
To create a paginated operation you will have to do:
```dataweave
@OperationElement()
var getUsersPaginated = offsetPaginated(
  getUsers,
  (page) -> page.body.items default [],
  (param) -> param.from default 0,
  (param, offset) -> (param update { case from at .from! -> offset })
)
```
## Marker Pagination example

If a SaaS has the following endpoint:
http://www.mulesoft.com/users?markerToken=X&limit=Y

The Operation is represented as:
```dataweave
var getUsers : Operation<{markerToken?: String, limit: Number}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, markerToken?: String}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var markerParams = if(!isEmpty(parameter.markerToken)) ("?markerToken=" ++ parameter.markerToken! ++ "&limit=" ++ parameter.limit) else ("?limit=" ++ parameter.limit)
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users" ++ markerParams})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, markerToken?: String}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```
To create a paginated operation, you will have to do:
```dataweave
@OperationElement()
var getUsersPaginated = markerPaginated(
  getUsers,
  (page) -> page.body.items default [],
  (page) -> page.body.markerToken default "",
  (param, marker) -> (param update { case markerToken at .markerToken! -> marker })
)

var getUsersPaginatedCustom = getUsersPaginated mapInputOperation (param: {limit: Number}) -> param // A mapInputOperation to define the input type operation to expose only
                                                       // limit: Number but (not closed) the mapping propagates the input
                                                       // therefore as the args is generated with a markerToken this one is
                                                       // sent to the base (decorated) operation but not exposed to consumers
                                                       // of this operation.
```
## Hypermedia Pagination example

### Always the same endpoint

If a SaaS has the following endpoint:
http://www.mulesoft.com/users?pageMarker=X&limit=Y and the response body as a field named `nextUrl`

The Operation is represented as:
```dataweave
var getUsers : Operation<{pageMarker?: String, limit?: Number}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users?pageMarker=" ++ (parameter.pageMarker default "") ++ "&limit=" ++ (parameter.limit default "")})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```
To create a paginated operation you will have to do:
```dataweave
@OperationElement()
var getUsersPaginated = hypermediaPaginated(
   getUsers,
   (page) -> page.body.items default [],
   (page) -> page.body.nextUrl  default "",
   (param, nextUrl) -> parseQueryParameters(nextUrl)
)
```
See how here the last lambda parameter defines the operation input parameter. In this example is only
defined by the `{pageMarker?: String, limit?: Number}` structure. Using the util `parseQueryParameters`, we are extracting
the query parameters from the `nextUrl` value, generating the same input operation parameter. There are other cases where the input
parameter defined by the operation is a complex object, so what is needed there is to define it as it is defined by the operation:

```dataweave
type OperationInputType = {uri: Object, query: Object}
@OperationElement()
var getUsersPaginated = hypermediaPaginated(
   getUsers,
   (page) -> page.body.items default [],
   (page) -> page.body.nextUrl  default "",
   (param, nextUrl) -> {uri: param.uri, query: parseQueryParameters(nextUrl) } 
)
```

### Different endpoint on second call
If a SaaS has the following endpoints:
http://www.mulesoft.com/users and http://www.mulesoft.com/more/{queryLocator} and the response body as a field named `nextUrl`

The Operations are represented as:
```dataweave
var getUsers : Operation<{}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users"})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```

```dataweave
var getMore : Operation<{queryLocator: String}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getMore",
    displayName: "Get More",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/more/" ++ parameter.queryLocator})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```

To create a paginated operation you will have to do:

```dataweave
var getMorePaginated = getMore paginated (param, page) -> {
    items: page.body.items default [],
    (nextPage: {
        args: {queryLocator: (splitBy(page.body.nextUrl, "/")[-1] default "")}
    }) if (!isEmpty(page.body.items) and !isEmpty(page.body.nextUrl))
}

var getUsersPaginated = paginatedWithNextPageOp(getUsers, getMorePaginated, (param, page) -> {
    items: page.body.items default [],
    (nextPage: {
        args: {queryLocator: (splitBy(page.body.nextUrl, "/")[-1] default "")}
    }) if (!isEmpty(page.body.items) and !isEmpty(page.body.nextUrl))
})
```

# Describing Errors
Sometimes operations can fail in different ways, for example when connecting to
Http Endpoints, an external service can fail with several status codes.

```dataweave
var getUsers : Operation<{}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>, ResultFailure<HttpResponse, Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users"})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response as HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>)
        else
          failure(response)
    }
}
```
Describing an operation in that way, will provide the user only the information that something failed and will return a `HttpResponse<Any>` as value, but the error kind and categories will be empty.

### Describing Error Types
If we want to provide the operation user the capability to handle certain Error Types, for example when an 404 occurs, we have to redefine the Operation.

```dataweave
type Error404 = Error<"404", "CLIENT_ERROR">

var Error404Instance : Error404 = {
  kind : "404",
  categories : ["CLIENT_ERROR"]
}

var getUsers : Operation<{}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>, ResultFailure<String, Error404 | Error>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users"})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response)
        else if (response.status == 404) 
          failure("404", Error404Instance)  
        else
          failure("unknown error")
    }
}
```
With this change, the operation consumer will be able to handle the 404 error kind, in runtime if the operation fail with 404, the error kind will be populated with 404

### Describing Multiple Error Values

Some External Systems depending on the Error Type, for example, 4XX or 5XX return different messages.

```dataweave
type Error404 = Error<"404", "CLIENT_ERROR">

var Error404Instance : Error404 = {
  kind : "404",
  categories : ["CLIENT_ERROR"]
}

type Error500 = Error<"500", "SERVER_ERROR">

var Error500Instance : Error500 = {
  kind: "500",
  categories: ["SERVER_ERROR"]
}

type 404ErrorMessage = {
  message : String
}

type 500ErrorMessage = {
  errorCode: Number 
}

var getUsers : Operation<{}, HttpResponse<{items: Array<{id: String, name: String, email: String}>, nextUrl?: String}>, ResultFailure<404ErrorMessage, Error404> | ResultFailure<500ErrorMessage, Error500>, HttpConnection> = {
    name: "getUsers",
    displayName: "Get Users",
    executor: (parameter, connection) -> do {
        var response = connection({method: 'GET', path: "/users"})
        ---
        if (response.status == 200)
          success(response)
        else if (response.status == 404) 
          failure({message: "404 Not Found"}, Error404Instance)  
        else
          failure({errorCode: 500}, Error500Instance})
    }
}
```
In this case, when the Saas fails with a 4xx, the error message value will be {message: String}, but in case the error is 5xx, the error shape will be {errorCode: Number}.
This change provides to the operation consumer the ability to, depending on the Error kind, determine the error message shape, to manipulate it.
